^B@2hondo717: Now, let me discuss an alternative to 2NT asking for feature, known as Ogust. There is another way to play a 2N response to a weak 2, known as Ogust. It allows the weak 2 opener to describe both his suit quality and high card points. The opener has a "good" suit if his suit contains two of the top three honors (e.g. AK, AQ, or KQ.) And the opener has a "good" hand if he is at the upper end of his range, 8-10 HCP. |
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


nt|
^b@2hondo717: So, if responder bids 2N, opener can describe whether or not he has both a good hand and a good suit. With a bad hand and a bad suit, he makes the cheapest bid, 3@C. It says nothing about clubs, only that opener has a bad hand and bad suit. All Ogust responses are completely artificial. Conversely, with a good hand and a good suit, opener makes the max bid, 3@S. A 3@D response shows a bad hand (5-7) and good suit and 3@H shows a good hand (8-10) and bad suit. I like that system better, because responder is now usually able to accurately place the final contract. But, many people do play feature. |
