^D@21) If I make a minor raise (to either the 2 level or 3 level), I am guaranteed to have no 4 card major.  @E@3 

2) I make a jump raise (to the 3 level) with 5 to a bad 9 points and 5+ card suit. I might have the other minor, but feel that the jump raise is tactically the right thing to do to make it difficult for the opponents. I will tend to prefer the jump raise to a bid of 1N if I have 5 card support.

3) I make a limit raise with 10+ points and usually 5 card support. (The only time I will have 4 card support is if I am 4-4 in the minors and partner opens 1D.) If partner opens clubs, I will not have 4 diamonds. If partner opens diamonds, I will not have 5+ clubs (in sayc; in 2 over 1,  1@D/2@C is slightly more complicated). Opener should now respond with his lowest stopper. If responder has less than a game forcing hand, he should continue to bid stoppers below 3 of the agreed upon suit, or 2N if he has all the other suits stopped. If responder has a game forcing hand, he must make sure the partnership bids game, by either bidding 3N if all suits are stopped, or continue bidding new suits if not. Similarly, if opener has 15+, it is his responsibility to make sure the partnership reaches games, by either bidding 3N if all suits are stopped, or continuing to bid new suits if not. Once 3 suits have been bid (the original suit and 2 stopper suits), if someone bids the 4th suit, that is asking about a stopper rather than telling, because if the bidder has the remaining suit stopped, he can bid NT himself.

4) Inverted minors are off in competition (including over takeout doubles), in the sense that a raise to 2 is less than a limit raise. A raise to 3 is still preemptive. With a limit raise or better, responder cue bids over an overcall, and bids Jordan 2N (if the partnership is playing it) or redoubles (if the partnership is not playing Jordan) over a takeout double. |
